31,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2487031,For Sale/Trade:  Springfield 1911 Loaded w/ night sights and extra mags,"Glendale, Phoenix, Arizona",$ 900,"Listed On: Tuesday, December 24, 2013",Handguns,Springfield                                                                                ,45 ACP                                                                                ,Single Action                                                                                ,Pistol,"Looking to sell or trade my Springfield 1911 Loaded. I'm getting away from 45acp as I have switched my primary carry caliber to 357sig, and this is the last of my 45s. Factory parkerized finish, factory night sights. I have 4 magazines for it, 2 factory 7 rounders, a Kimber 8 round and a Novak 8 rounc. I do not have the factory holster or mag carrier that came with it, took them out of the case and they disappeared at some point from my gear cabinet.

My gun has an extremely low round count (in the neighborhood of 250, has never seen the inside of a holster. It is completely factory, the trigger was adjusted for minimal reset travel. It also includes a set of VZ Recon grips to sweeten the deal.
I also have over 150 rounds of Factory FMJ 230gr ammo and 12 rounds of premium JHP ammo, that I can include for another $75.

Gun runs extremely well and is super accurate, I just really don't want to deal with setting up to reload 45acp, but if I can't get my asking price or a decent trade before the end of the year I will just move ahead with reloading 45acp and keep the gun.
Price is firm at $825 without the ammo or $900 with the ammo. Trade value $1000, and will come with the ammo.
(I'm not willing to sell the ammo before the gun is gone, no PM's about the ammo until I list it separately)

Please keep trade offers reasonable, my asking price is about $200 less than than I have into this, and my trade value is still $100 less than I have into this. I am not going to consider low offers, as I have no ""need"" to sell or trade this gun, other than convenience."

MOE® Carbine Stock – Mil-Spec Model

Magpul Original Equipment (MOE) is a line of firearm accessories designed to provide a high-quality, economical alternative to standard weapon parts. The MOE line distinguishes itself with a simplified feature set, but maintains Magpul engineering and material quality.

The Magpul MOE Stock – Mil-Spec Model is a drop-in replacement buttstock for AR15/M16 carbines using mil-spec sized receiver extension tubes. Designed for light, fast action the streamlined A-frame profile avoids snagging and shields the release latch to prevent accidental activation. The Mil-Spec Model includes a standard 0.30"" rubber butt-pad which provides positive shoulder purchase to prevent slippage even with body armor or modular gear.
MOE® Grip – AR15/M16

The MOE Grip provides Magpul quality, feel, and durability in an economical, drop-in upgrade for the standard AR15/M16/M4 pistol grip. The ergonomic, hand filling design combines aggressive texturing with storage core capability. With a similar shape to a 'medium' sized MIAD, the one-piece reinforced polymer construction provides simplicity and a reduced cost while still maintaining the durability needed to withstand operational environments. The MOE Grip accepts optional storage cores for gear stowage and includes a basic grip cap. All mounting hardware included."

WESSON/ MANUFACTURER/ WORCESTER MASS/ 1854-65, Springfield MA 1865-75 PATENT APPLIED/ FOR."") “Blade” brass sights, with the center section textured and a serrated release button on the underside of the frame. Trigger housing: Brass
Barrel Markings: ""unknown… D MASS PT DEC 15/68 - visible under magnification
Gauge: 32 Rimfire
Finish: blue/ silver
Grips: rosewood Birds head
Serial Number: 1235

Condition:  Rosewood birds head grips very good, small chip left side, original finish still present. Mechanical function good, hammer smooth and tight, ½ cock safety fully functional.  Barrels exhibit rust under naked eye, pitting visible under jewelers loop.  All original parts finish is worn; rated none to 30%, all original metal, smooth, wood smooth good finish, lettering visible under magnification.
NRA ANTIQUE FIREARM STANDARDS
VERY GOOD: All original parts; none to 30% original finish; original metal surfaces smooth with all edges sharp; clear lettering, numerals and design on metal; wood slightly scratched or
bruised; bore disregarded for collectors firearms.

GOOD: Some minor replacement parts; metal smoothly rusted or lightly pitted in places, cleaned or re-blued; principal letters, numerals and design on metal legible; wood refinished, scratched bruised or minor cracks repaired; in good working order.
Based on above this 1868 vintage superposed pistol is rated good to V. Good.
Caliber .32 Short rim fire was designed in 1860 by Smith & Wesson for their Model 2 revolver. In 1868 they introduced the .32 Long in the Model 1½ Second Issue revolver.

The .32 Short fired an 80 grain lead bullet at 945 feet per second from a 24-inch rifle barrel. The .32 Long fired a slightly heavier 90 grain bullet at approximately the same velocity. Remington rifles in .32 rimfire listed a bore diameter of .304 inch."

Located in Bald Knob Arkansas. From what I have been able to research on this one, it is an Inland barrel and receiver with Inland flip lever safety, Underwood sear, and Saginaw slide. It's a 4 digit serial number, and from what I have found,  it was produced between 1942-43 with the serial number in the 5000s. The wood is in pretty good shape.
